[1] Brazil: (Alto Paranaíba) cattle
Date: Tue 22 Feb 2022
Source: Otempo [in Portuguese, machine trans., edited]
https://www.otempo.com.br/cidades/caso-de-raiva-em-bovino-de-patos-de-minas-mobiliza-prefeitura-1.2619328


After the notification of a positive case of rabies in a bovine in 1 of its districts, the Health Surveillance of the Municipality of Patos de Minas, in Alto Paranaíba, was mobilized to vaccinate dogs and cats in the region where the sick animal was found. The information was released by the municipality on Tuesday [22 Feb 2022]. In December of last year [2021], the City Hall also carried out the vaccine blockade in the region of Moreeiras, for the same reason.

The cattle testing positive for rabies was located in the community of Basilio, in the district of Areado, which is about 40 km [25 mi] from the city. The mobilization, which is called anti-rabies blockade, involved domestic animals within a 5 km [3 mi] radius of the place.

In all, 326 dogs and 111 cats were vaccinated. Part of them already received the vaccine in 2021, but were revaccinated according to the guidance of the competent state bodies. The city took the opportunity to guide the population on the importance of immunizing animals and ways of transmitting and preventing the disease.

"It is important to highlight that the vaccination of cattle and horses against rabies has become mandatory, on behalf of the owner of the animals, although the declaration to the Mineiro de Agropecuária Institute (IMA) is not mandatory. Anyway, this will help a lot to avoid occurrences like this", explains the director of Health Surveillance in the city, Lílian Marinho.

The professional also says the vaccination blockade of dogs and cats is a way to eliminate one of the cycles of transmission of the disease, since, if an animal was detected with rabies, it is because there are bats infected with the virus in the region and that could infect other mammals.

According to the Patos de Minas City Hall, rabies is transmitted by bats feeding on blood, the so-called hematophagous bats. [This is likely the species more commonly known as the vampire bat. - Mod.TG]

With the virus present in saliva, it transmits the disease by sucking or licking blood from mammals, such as horses, cattle, dogs and cats. Therefore, domestic animals are the main transmission agents for humans. [If this is the vampire bat, it most likely makes a tiny razor-like cut in the skin and then licks the blood from the wound. These bats are known to feed on cattle and horses, especially at night. - Mod.TG]

"Rabies is a serious disease, with a lethality rate close to 100%. For more information, contact the Zoonosis Control Center by phone at (34) 3822-9624 (7am to 6pm)", concludes the municipality.

