Communicated by:
ProMED

[In the 1st article from Brazil, the bat in question is most likely what is commonly known as the vampire bat. It is known for feeding on cattle and a host of other animals. There are 3 species of hematophagous bats in the Neotropical region, one of which -- _Desmodus rotundus_ -- is a well-known reservoir of rabies. This species feeds on a wide range of hosts, including humans, although it will preferentially feed on large livestock such as cattle and horses. For a picture of _D. rotundus_ go to https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/41168-Desmodus-rotundus/browse_photos.

Rabies is a viral disease affecting the central nervous system of its victim, regardless of whether it is a human victim or an animal victim. This virus has no mercy and without treatment, its victim will die.

While we recognize rabies prevention in the form of rabies vaccination for our animals, and for some high risk human beings, such as veterinarians and persons involved in animal control, it is not a wide spread practice to vaccinate human beings against rabies. Therefore, when an individual is exposed to this lethal virus, post exposure prophylaxis (PEP) must be administered. This is a series of human immunoglobulin and PEP to prevent rabies in human beings but it must be started very soon after the exposure. In the case of bats in a room where an individual was sleeping, PEP is recommended as bats can bite a sleeping individual and not awaken them.

If you have pets, including horses and other farm animals, it is the wise, prudent move to vaccinate them against rabies. It protects your pets and yourself. Even if you do not know if there has been exposure to your animal, you are more likely to be protected. - Mod.TG

